      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Top Temperature Distribution\n\n| Temperature (°C) | Count | % of Total |\n|------------------:|------:|-----------:|\n| 25.0 | 67,237 | 85.04% |\n| 20.0 | 6,845 | 8.66% |\n| 37.0 | 1,699 | 2.15% |\n| 30.0 | 919 | 1.16% |\n| 35.0 | 488 | 0.62% |\n| 18.0 | 482 | 0.61% |\n\nThe overwhelming dominance of 25 °C reflects the convention in solution thermodynamics of reporting equilibrium constants at this standard reference temperature. The next most common temperature, 20 °C (8.7%), was historically popular in European laboratories, while 37 °C (2.2%) corresponds to physiological temperature — measurements at that value are typically motivated by biomedical or clinical chemistry applications.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes)*",
